    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>New Orleans</placeName>
                <date>May 3.5613</date>
            </p>
            <p>My dear friend</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Yours <date>20<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date>
                <add>?</add> came to hand a<lb/> couple of days ago and I proceed to answer<lb/> its
                most important portion viz. I spoke<lb/> for a considerable length of time to
                    <persName>Mr. Touro</persName> in your behalf stating what I<lb/> think he ought
                to do for you and other<lb/> as is my practice with him, left him<lb/> to ponder the
                matter. Meeting<lb/> with him again next day I asked<lb/> him if he had come to any
                conclu<lb/>sion in the premises upon which<lb/> he replied that (as I happen to
                know<lb/> to be the case <hi rend="underline">just now</hi>) he had not<lb/> enough
                money on hand to pay pressing<lb/> demands, but he added that he had<lb/> a balance
                of $300 in the hands of <persName>David<lb/> Hart Esq</persName>
                <placeName>New York</placeName> which he would order him<lb/> to remit to you. Now
                whether he intends<lb/> to send you $700 from here or not I can<lb/> not say. I did
                not like to press him<lb/> on this point because you know<lb/> he is a strange man,
                and intending to<lb/> serve you, I might have injured your<lb/> claims. I choose to
                infer that he<lb/> will send you the 700 and after some</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>little time elapses I shall inquire<lb/> of him if he has written to
                    <persName>Mr<lb/> Hart</persName> &amp; if he has sent you the 700.<lb/> I think
                he will do it sooner or<lb/> later.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I thank you for the information<lb/> given in your letter. Your note to<lb/>
                <persName>Mr Isaac Hart</persName> I duly delivered.<lb/> With regard to publishing
                    <persName>Dias's</persName> letter<lb/> you will meet with poor support<lb/>
                here. I suppose 20 <del>or 30</del> copies could<lb/> be disposed of here in both
                congregations<lb/> provided the price does not exceed<lb/> 50 to 75 cents.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Mr de Sola </persName>of <placeName>Canada</placeName>
                sent some<lb/> 40 copies of <persName>English's</persName> work <add>?</add>
                and<lb/> a number of pamphlets on the Sermon<lb/> on the
                    <placeName>Mount</placeName>. I believe about <hi rend="underline">10</hi><lb/>
                of the former only have been sold altho'<lb/>
                <persName>Gutheim</persName> &amp; myself have tried to keep the sale.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Your Book, <add>Bible</add>left with me by <persName>Mr<lb/>
                    Nathan</persName> I will bear in mind<lb/> altho' I fear it will be a long
                time<lb/> before I can sell them.</p>
            <p>When your new Bible comes out<lb/> have the copy which I ordered for<lb/> myself
                strongly and handsomely bound<lb/> and my name printed on the cover</p>
            <pb n="2R"/>
            <p>a few dollars more or less you need<lb/> not consider in my case.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I am still in correspondence with<lb/>
                <persName>Mr Eckman</persName> about <placeName>China</placeName>. His<lb/> advices
                from <persName>Dr. Adler</persName> are unsatisfactory<lb/> and yet I think I know
                the Jews<lb/> in this country too well, to believe<lb/> that anything will be done
                on this<lb/> side of the <placeName>Atlantic</placeName>. There are some<lb/>
                disturbances in <placeName>China</placeName> &amp; throughout<lb/> the
                    <placeName>East</placeName> &amp; I pray the finger of Providence<lb/> may yet
                point out a release for the<lb/> unfortunate of our faith in the<lb/> Chinese
                Empire. Oh <persName>Leeser</persName> if I had<lb/> the wealth of some of my
                intimate<lb/> friends. What can I do? I assure<lb/> you no one knows how much I<lb/>
                have to do here in every way, in<lb/> everything connected with Judaism<lb/> many
                are the hours that I feel<lb/> so sick at heart that if I could<lb/> I would go and
                live beyond the reach<lb/> of man or at least of my own people.<lb/> I am poor and
                as yet have not<lb/> been able to pay off debts honorably<lb/> incurred in my
                previous unfortunate<lb/> business. It is a great question in my<lb/> mind if I have
                the right to do the<lb/> little charity which I do whilst I</p>
            <pb n="2V"/>
            <p>am in debt; and then my very<lb/> manner of living, which is some-<lb/> what
                expensive and which nevertheless<lb/> I ought to continue for very many<lb/> good
                reasons, compels me to curtail<lb/> at times the amounts which I would<lb/>
                otherwise give away. But I hope<lb/> to continue to prosper in the world<lb/> in
                order to extend the benefits which<lb/> I ought bestow on others.</p>
            <p rend="indent(7)">If I do not hear before long of a<lb/> proper person to fill the
                office of<lb/> Minister to our congregation, I think<lb/> I shall propose to the men
                here to alter<lb/> our advertisement simply to call<lb/> for a first rate Portuguese
                Hazan and<lb/> this I will do because I see now<lb/> that the majority care more for the<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">singing</hi> than for the preaching—<lb/> I have found it
                imperative upon me<lb/> even at this late day to pursue the course<lb/> recommended
                by <persName>Mr Calhoun</persName>
                <add>?</add> “Masterly inac<lb/>tivity.” I have too much <hi rend="underline">dead
                    weight</hi> to<lb/> contend against &amp; after struggling for<lb/> an end for
                nearly a score of years I have<lb/> now to yield, till a new generation arises<lb/>
                which so far as I can I am impregnating with the broad views &amp; philanthropy of
                the<lb/> Mosaic teachings. My sister, Brother &amp; theirs send you fond greetings.
                I am yours as ever faithfully,</p>
            <p rend="indent(7)">
                <persName role="author">Gershom K.</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
    </text>
